{
  "answer": "**In the Old Javanese Śaivite *tattva* texts, \"jñāna\" (Sanskrit ज्ञान) appears frequently transliterated as *jñāna*, retaining its core Sanskritic sense as salvific, self-revelatory wisdom—especially *ātma-jñāna* (knowledge of the Self)—without translation into Kawi vernaculars.[^1][^2]**\n\nA pinpoint example is from *Saṅ Hyaṅ Mahājñāna* (\"The Sacred Supreme Wisdom\"), a tantric dialogue between Kumāra and Śiva on cosmology, physiology, and non-dual realization:\n\n> *rātriś ca prakṛtir jñeyā raviś ca puruṣas tathā /  \n> ātmajñānaṃ tu vijñāya mucyate nātra saṃśayaḥ // 12*[^3]\n\n**Translation:** \"The *pradhāna* (*prakṛti*) is the night. The revered *puruṣa* is the sun that rises in the night. The holy *ātmā* is said to be *jñāna* (wisdom/knowledge). When one knows all of this, let there be no doubt that one returns to the abode of the Lord.\"[^4]\n\nHere, *jñāna*/*ātma-jñāna* effects *mukti* (liberation) via gnosis of *prakṛti*/*puruṣa* polarity, mirroring Sanskritic usages in *Bhagavad Gītā* 4.34 (guru-imparted discriminative wisdom) or *Śiva Sūtras* (non-dual Self-knowledge dissolving saṃsāra). No doctrinal shift: the Kawi frame adapts Śaiva Siddhānta/Abhinavagupta-style *jñāna-mārga* to Javanese *liṅga*-worship and *oṃkāra*-meditation, where *jñāna* pierces *māyā* toward *śiva-pada* (Śiva-abode), as in later verses equating it with *tattva*-cognition for *kaivalya*.[^5]\n\nThis holds across *tattva*-corpus (*Saṅ Hyaṅ Tattvajñāna* titles it as \"Tattvajñāna,\" Knowledge of 36 *tattva*s; *Gaṇapatitattva* links to *jñāna-śakti* of Sadāśiva).[^6] It functions as tantric praxis-tool, not diluted philosophy.",
